Q11.1: robust risk assessment...but.... given the data available
Q13.15: Industry mainly acts indirectly in conditioning the evalutions of independent agencies, by paving the (back)ground for risk assessment: / - via new products to be launched on the market and risk assessment therein of (A), but also  / - via procedures, methodologies and protocols (see the Thresholds of Toxicological Concern TTC advanced in last years);  / - via research projects -grants-fundings. also at the EC level (i.e., Horizon 2020 etc) under a public shield reputation. / Efsa may well behave at its best and gifted with the most talented scientists, but with often limited datasets-studies and in condition of urgency for adoption of the technologies (market pressure). Whoever acts as "first mover" and distribute the playing cards has an inherent advantage and so the industry. Hence whilst  Efsa may be the best organisation in place to do its work, "you cannot swim like Michale Phelps in a swamp" to use a metaphore. The lack of ability to replicate the studies is key. Also is not possible to charge double cost to industry to replicate the studies via independent laboratories due to the "law shopping" (i.e. industry may select more relaxed countries with easiest risk assessment procedures and exit the EU market as a whole and signals of this kind were made in the past). The paradox stems probably from a form of cognitive trap or bias, let's say, "institutional bias"("newly minted coin" FOR YOU GUYS) for which each problem requires a body or institution, followed by the faith that the mere presence of the body or institution will be able- with the proper resources- to act properly and solve the problems it is designed to do.
survey.name: EFSA_survey2_power_group

Q13.15: I found that the survey was vague at some points. For example, if the methodologies used by a European agency are actually co-written/co-developed by scientists paid by industry sector, then even if the agency applies the methodologies correctly, the assessment will be biased. Also the new technologies always depend on how you will use them. You may use artificial intelligence to help the public sector and improve human and environmental well being or you may use them to increase profit even if this promotes biodiversity collapse or poverty in certain areas of the world.

Q1.3_7_TEXT: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; Win64; x64; rv:66.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/66.0
Q13.15: The questions you pose on EFSA indicate a fundamental misunderstanding about its practical functioning. Unlike ECHA and EMA - it is COMPLETELY IMPOSSIBLE for industry to interact with EFSA. You are only allowed to submit documents within the process - no explanations can be given, no context nor questions from the agency. In essence you throw the dossier over the wall and you hope that you understood what was required and that they understand what you are saying. The closed nature of the process leads to extreme frustrations by all parties as at times you see that you are misunderstood and yet there is no opportunity to explain and sometimes you get outcomes that are unexpected and you are left with the feeling you dont understand why that happened. / As regards the case of Flupy - which as it happens my colleagues worked on - its a bad example to take. The ED definitions are still pending and everything depends on them to correctly answer some of the questions you ask. If ED is defined broadly - potential ED effects for example - the outcome might be different than if there was a separation on potency or risk. I am not saying one is right or the other is wrong - I am just saying that EFSA's opinion might change if you change the definition and therefore the opinion as it stands is neither right nor wrong. It is what it is based on what is known today.
survey.name: EFSA_SURVEY_06

Q1.3_7_TEXT: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; Trident/7.0; SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; Media Center PC 6.0; .NET4.0C; .NET4.0E; InfoPath.3; Zoom 3.6.0; wbx 1.0.0; rv:11.0) like Gecko
Q11.1: not involving the right regulatory scientists and only academic researchers, without knowledge of Regulatory Sciences and how the EU works (laws and decision making!)
Q13.15: Yes, there are several mistakes in this survey. One of them is for example calling EFSA a Regulator, which is not the case. EFSA is a consulting agency for the Commission (in the case of Pesticides) and is issuing a "Scientific Opinion", not a regulatory decision (contrary to Regulatory Agencies such as EMA and ECHA, which are de facto regulators). Also EFSA relies on Academics which are not experts in Regulatory Sciences as the other Agencies (Echa and EMA).
survey.name: EFSA_SURVEY_06

Q13.15: The direction that the EU is going (conservative upon conservativism leading to non-renewal of pesticides) will result in a negative influence on their own growers.  The whole data transparency issue will also result in new, safer technologies not being brought to the EU due to loss of confidentiality.  While EU has a mandate for innovation, the direction is leading to a complete loss of innovation.  Ultimately, only the rich will be able to afford imported foods and less fortunate people will be challenged to afford quality food.  The "industry" are people too, committed to feeding people, preserving the environment, etc.
